"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777688","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-02","<p>The latest available data is for new claims to UC Full Service that are due a payment in the week from 14 August 2017. For this group of claims, we find that 95% - 97% receive full payment ‘within 10 weeks of submitting a claim’.</p><p> </p><p>These results may be revised as further data becomes available.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","109510","2017-11-02T16:08:52.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777688/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777688/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-25","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of claimants of universal credit did not receive the full payment within 10 weeks of submitting a claim.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","109509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777689","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-02","<p>The latest available data is for new claims to UC Full Service that are due a payment in the week from 14 August 2017. For this group of claims, we find that 95% - 97% receive full payment ‘within 10 weeks of submitting a claim’.</p><p> </p><p>These results may be revised as further data becomes available.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","109509","2017-11-02T16:08:53.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777689/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777689/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-25","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of new claimants of universal credit did not receive the full payment within 10 weeks of submitting a claim.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","109510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777690","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-30","<p>This information is not available.</p><p> </p><p>Only Employment and Support Allowance and Universal Credit equivalent claimants, with the most severe and lifelong health condition or disabilities, who are unlikely to ever be able to move in to work, will fall within this criteria. We expect the majority of these claimants will be assessed on paper, and will not need a face to face assessment</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-10-30T11:09:51.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777690/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777690/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-25","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of decisions on whether employment and support allowance claimants will not have to undergo further work capability assessments as a result of a lifelong, progressive, degenerative or incurable condition will be made as a result of a paper-based assessment.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","109515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777691","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-30","<p>Automatic enrolment was introduced to help people save for their retirement, particularly lower earners and women who were poorly served by existing provision</p><p> </p><p>Over the next two years contribution levels will be increasing gradually; for an individual, these are currently at 1 per cent, rising to 3 per cent in April 2018 and 5 per cent in April 2019. Employers and individuals can already pay in more than the legal minimum should they wish, and some already do.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently reviewing automatic enrolment to build on its success to date; this includes looking at how individuals can be helped to have a stronger sense of personal ownership of their workplace pensions, and be better enabled to maximise retirement savings.</p><p> </p><p>The review work is led by a DWP team and supported by an external advisory group. We will report to Parliament by the end of 2017.</p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-10-30T14:18:36.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777691/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777691/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-25","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to support people in automatic enrolment pension schemes to make additional voluntary contributions to their pensions.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","109482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777692","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-31","<p>The independent Cost of Energy Review was carried out by Professor Dieter Helm and published on 25 October.</p><p> </p><p>Professor Helm has been subject to the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-7-principles-of-public-life/the-7-principles-of-public-life--2" target="_blank">Nolan Principles</a> of conduct in public life throughout the conduct of his review, and committed to not advise clients in the energy sector throughout, and to not make changes to relevant financial interests until fourteen days after he submitted the report.</p><p> </p><p>All evidence shared by the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) with Professor Helm is in the public domain. BEIS does not hold non-public information on any of Professor Helm’s financial interests.</p><p> </p><p>This was an independent review. The Government will consider Professor Helm’s recommendations and will shortly be seeking the views of industry, academics, businesses and consumer groups on the review.</p><p> </p><p>Given the long-term nature of the issues considered in the review, and the steps set out above, it would not be proportionate to restrict Professor Helm’s future activities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","109380 ; 109381 ; 109382 ; 109383 ; 109426 ; 109427 ; 109428","2017-10-31T11:25:57.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777692/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777692/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-25","Cost of Energy Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 24 October 2017 to Question 107371, who drafted the document entitled Professor Dieter Helm - declaration of interest.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","109477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777693","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-31","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority recommended in their 2016 report that Ofgem remove the simpler tariff rules. These rules banned suppliers from offering complex tariffs and capped the number of tariffs which they could offer. Ofgem have now introduced new rules governing the information about tariffs which suppliers can give to their domestic customers in their sales and marketing activities, including a requirement that they should be easily comparable. Government supports this approach.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-31T14:55:55.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777693/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777693/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-25","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent progress he has made to simplify the number of tariffs offered by energy companies.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","109514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777694","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-30","<p>As set out in the UK-EU letter of the 11 October 2017, in order to minimise disruption to global trade as we leave the EU, we will replicate as far as possible, our current obligations in the World Trade Organization (WTO). We recognise that tariff rate quotas are a particularly complex issue and we are working closely with the EU and other WTO members to maintain existing levels of market access.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","109485","2017-10-30T17:21:32.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777694/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777694/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-25","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether the revised tariff rate quotas for the UK that will be lodged with the WTO will constitute a technical rectification.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","109483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777695","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-30","<p>The UK and the EU have proposed an approach that would minimise disruption to trade with other WTO member states by maintaining the current levels of market access set out in our WTO schedules.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-30T17:06:46.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777695/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777695/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-25","World Trade Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the effect of the UK and EU's joint position on WTO schedules of commitments on other WTO member states.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","109484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777696","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-30","<p>As set out in the UK-EU letter of the 11 October 2017, in order to minimise disruption to global trade as we leave the EU, we will replicate as far as possible, our current obligations in the World Trade Organization (WTO). We recognise that tariff rate quotas are a particularly complex issue and we are working closely with the EU and other WTO members to maintain existing levels of market access.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","109483","2017-10-30T17:21:32.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777696/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777696/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-25","World Trade Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what plans he has to facilitate the implementation of the UK's schedules and quotas at the WTO under the modification procedure.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","109485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777697","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-30","<p>This Department is preparing the necessary schedules, so that they are ready for when the UK leaves the European Union (EU) on 29 March 2019.</p><p>It should also be noted that the UK is a full and founding member of the World Trade Organization and already has schedules which it shares at present with the EU Member States.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-30T17:13:26.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777697/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777697/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-25","World Trade Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has made of the date when schedules and tariff rate quotas for the UK will be agreed at the WTO.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","109486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777698","Attorney General","false","2017-11-01","<p>The Government is carrying out an ongoing programme of comprehensive analytical work that will inform our negotiating position with the EU, to define our deep and special partnership with the EU and inform our understanding of how EU exit will affect the UK’s domestic policies and frameworks.</p><p>The Law Officers’ Departments are working with officials across government, in close coordination with the Department for Exiting the European Union, to ensure the delivery of a co-ordinated programme of analysis across government.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2017-11-01T14:08:08.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777698/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777698/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-10-25","Attorney General: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, whether the Law Officers' Departments were consulted by the Department for Exiting the European Union on the economic impact assessments conducted for the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","109528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777699","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-14","<p>The Government is carrying out an ongoing programme of comprehensive analytical work that will inform our negotiating position with the EU, to define our deep and special partnership with the EU and inform our understanding of how EU exit will affect the UK’s domestic policies and frameworks</p><p><br> Cabinet Office is working with officials across government, in close coordination with the Department for Exiting the European Union, to ensure the delivery of a holistic programme of analysis across government.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-11-14T10:34:44.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777699/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777699/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-25","Cabinet Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department was consulted by the Department for Exiting the European Union on the economic impact assessments conducted for the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","109529"
