"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777850","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>Since 2008, the Home Office have resettled over 380 refugees to the UK under the Mandate scheme.</p><p>The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees can refer any case meeting the scheme’s criteria to the Home Office for consideration and there is no fixed annual quota.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-01T09:50:55.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777850/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777850/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","Refugees: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to increase the number of refugee families reunited under the Mandate scheme.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","109687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777851","Home Office","false","2017-11-02","<p>Our work to tackle knife crime is centred on four key strands – working with the police on operations and enforcement, work on legislative framework, work with retailers on responsible sales, and early intervention and prevention.</p><p> </p><p>We are encouraging police forces to undertake a series of coordinated national weeks of action to tackle knife crime under Operation Sceptre. The operation includes targeting habitual knife carriers, weapon sweeps, test purchases of knives from identified retailers, and the use of surrender bins. A record thirty-two police forces took part in the week of action in July.</p><p> </p><p>We have also agreed a set of commitments with major retailers to prevent the underage sales of knives more generally in their stores and online. The agreement also covers staff training and displays and packaging.</p><p> </p><p>We are keeping the legislative framework under review and on 14 October we launched a consultation on new legislation on offensive weapons. The proposals include placing restrictions on the online sale of knives, creating a new offence of possession of an offensive or dangerous weapon in a private place, and updating existing legislation. We have also just launched a £500,000 community fund to help community and voluntary sector organisations respond to knife crime, and we are supporting youth violence intervention and prevention work in hospital emergency departments. We are also intending to have national media campaign shortly aimed at discouraging young people from carrying knives.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-11-02T16:37:23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777851/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777851/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","Knives: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to reduce knife crime.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","109595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777852","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>Approximately 850 UK linked individuals of national security concern have travelled to engage with the Syrian conflict. We estimate that just under half have returned and approximately 15% are now dead. This number includes all those of national security concern, not just those affiliated with Daesh. Everyone who returns from taking part in the conflict in Syria or Iraq must expect to be investigated by the police to determine if they have committed criminal offences, and to ensure that they do not pose a threat to our national security.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-11-01T13:36:14.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777852/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777852/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","British Nationals Abroad: Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many British citizens have returned to the UK after fighting in Iraq and Syria since 2012.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","109589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777853","Home Office","true","2017-11-01","<p><del class="ministerial">A small number of shooting clubs are approved to use firearms which use armour-piercing ammunition.</del></p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial">The possession of armour-piercing or explosive ammunition is prohibited under section 5 of the Firearms Act 1968 and can only be used with the</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">authority of the Secretary of State. No such authority has been granted for the use of such ammunition by civilian target shooting clubs.</ins></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-01T13:26:14Z","2017-11-17T16:44:26.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777853/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777853/answer","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777853/answer/previousversion/19267","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","Gun Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether any civilian target shooting club in the UK is approved by her Department to use armour piercing or explosive ammunition.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","109587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777854","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>On 14 October the Government launched a public consultation on proposals to strengthen controls on offensive and dangerous weapons, including the prohibition of two types of firearm: .50 calibre ‘materiel destruction’ rifles and rapid fire rifles, such as the VZ58 Manually Actuated Release System (MARS) rifle. The consultation closes on 9 December.</p><p>The Fifty Calibre Shooters Association has requested a meeting with officials to discuss the proposals and this is being arranged. We have not had a similar request from the National Rifle Association but would welcome their views.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-01T13:27:06.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777854/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777854/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","Rifles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has met representatives of the (a) FCSA UK club or (b) National Rifle Association to discuss her Department's proposals on banning .50 calibre rifles.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","109591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777855","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>To be approved by the Home Office, shooting clubs must comply with the criteria for approval as published under the terms of section 15(3) of the Firearms (Amendment) Act 1988.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-01T13:27:49.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777855/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777855/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","Gun Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what criteria her Department uses to formally approve target shooting clubs; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","109592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777856","Home Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>The Home Office currently processes several million immigration decisions each year and takes steps to ensure that the necessary resources are provided to process applications. The Home Office has well-developed processes for modelling operational demand that will be used as appropriate to support internal capacity planning.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-30T16:52:13.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777856/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777856/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","Visas: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to ensure that UK Visas and Immigration has an adequate number of staff to process Tier 2 visa applications when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","109649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777857","Home Office","false","2017-11-03","<p>The Government does not maintain a central register of ‘slavery and human trafficking statements’ published in accordance with section 54 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015. Two independent repository websites have been set up to collate these statements. The Government is not involved in running or funding either website. Both websites make different estimates of the total number of statements published so far. The latest estimates can be accessed online at <a href="http://www.modernslaveryregistry.org/" target="_blank">http://www.modernslaveryregistry.org/</a> and <a href="https://tiscreport.org/" target="_blank">https://tiscreport.org/</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-11-03T10:03:05.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777857/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777857/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many companies published a Modern Slavery Statement in accordance with the provisions of section 54 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015 in (a) 2016 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Alex Norris","Nottingham North","Alex Norris","109691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777858","Home Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>We support the principle of family unity and recognise that reuniting refugees in the UK with their immediate family can help with the integration process by providing support to participate in the economic, social, cultural, civil and political life of this country.</p><p>Our family reunion policy has seen over 24,000 family reunion visas granted in the last five years.</p><p>Refugees and those who benefit from family reunion visas are entitled to broadly the same rights and benefits as British citizens, including access to the labour market and mainstream benefits to support their integration. Refugees are also able to apply for an integration loan.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-30T16:46:36.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777858/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777858/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","Refugees: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of the refugee family reunion rules on the capacity of refugees to integrate fully in the UK.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","109651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777859","Home Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>The specific information you have requested is not currently published.</p><p>Published statistics on visa applications in the Family category can be found online at the following address: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/638590/entry-visas1-apr-jun-2017-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/638590/entry-visas1-apr-jun-2017-tables.ods</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-30T16:44:00Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777859/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777859/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","Refugees: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications for family reunion visas under part 11 of the Immigration Rules were granted outside of those rules in (a) 2014, (b) 2015 and (c) 2016.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","109652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777860","Home Office","false","2017-10-31","<p>I announced a review of the regulation of air weapons on Monday 9 October. Details of the scope of the review will be set out shortly</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-10-31T15:52:45.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777860/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777860/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","Rifles: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government plans to introduce a licensing regime for air rifles.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","109684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777861","Home Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>The Modern Slavery Helpline is operated by an organisation called Unseen, and is completely independent of Government.</p><p>Information about the number and types of calls received by the Modern Slavery Helpline can be found on the Unseen website <a href="http://www.modernslaveryhelpline.org/information/stats" target="_blank">www.modernslaveryhelpline.org/information/stats</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-10-30T17:17:36.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777861/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777861/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether an assessment of the (a) number and (b) types of calls made to the modern slavery helpline has been made since that helpline was established.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","109685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777862","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-14","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-11-14T11:12:51.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777862/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777862/answer","PQ 109607 v0.2.pdf","PQ 109607 v0.2.pdf","UKSA response","UKSA response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777862/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-25","EU Nationals: Emigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent estimate he has made of the number of non-UK EU citizens who have left the UK since 23 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","109607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777863","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Government is carrying out an ongoing programme of comprehensive analytical work that will inform our negotiating position with the EU, to define our deep and special partnership with the EU and inform our understanding of how EU exit will affect the UK’s domestic policies and frameworks.</p><p>My Department is working with officials across government, in close coordination with the Department for Exiting the European Union, to ensure the delivery of a holistic programme of analysis across government.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-07T16:16:25.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777863/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777863/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","Home Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department was consulted by the Department for Exiting the European Union on the economic impact assessments conducted for the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","109536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777864","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-01","<p>The Government is carrying out an ongoing programme of comprehensive analytical work that will inform our negotiating position with the EU, to define our deep and special partnership with the EU, and inform our understanding of how EU exit will affect the UK’s domestic policies and frameworks.</p><p>The Department for International Development is working with officials across government, in close coordination with the Department for Exiting the European Union, to ensure the delivery of a holistic programme of analysis across government.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-11-01T17:39:36.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777864/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777864/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-25","Department for International Development: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department was consulted by the Department for Exiting the European Union on the economic impact assessments conducted for the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","109537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777865","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-01","<p>In line with the International Development (Official Development Assistance Target) Act 2015 the government allocates sufficient funding to deliver the commitment to spend 0.7% of GNI in each calendar year.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-11-01T09:46:35.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777865/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777865/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-25","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, under what circumstances the Government would consider increasing the percentage  of GDP allocated to official development assistance above 0.7 per cent.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","109573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777866","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-01","<p>The UK is the second largest bilateral donor to the refugee response in Uganda. Our support is increasing to reflect rising needs from the recent influx of refugees, predominantly from South Sudan. In the coming year, we plan to provide food to more than 900,000 refugees, shelter to 116,000 refugees, access to clean water for more than 212,000 refugees and nutritional support to more than 215,000 children.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-11-01T09:45:38.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777866/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777866/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-25","Uganda: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department plans to take to support the Government of Uganda in supporting refugees in that country.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","109606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777867","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-30","<p>DFID’s 2016 Research Review confirmed our commitment to invest around 3% of its budget on research and innovation. Of over 180 projects, 80% are active in Africa.</p><p>This large footprint of research partnerships between UK and Africa have resulted in new evidence and technologies which are changing lives. DFID also supports investments to strengthen nationally-led investment in science, technology and innovation and research leadership in Africa.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-10-30T15:04:07.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777867/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777867/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-25","Africa: Innovation and Science","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps the Government is taking to support science and innovation in Africa.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","109677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777868","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>The British Council have advised that the African Knowledge Transfer Partnership (AKTP) pilot project ran from February 2011 - March 2013, and was jointly funded by the British Council and private companies.</p><p>It supported 40 UK – Sub Saharan Africa partnerships between commercial organisations and higher education institutions to help businesses improve their productivity and competitiveness harnessing scientific knowledge, technology and skills.</p><p>The British Council have no plans to replicate the project in the future.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-10-30T17:22:02.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777868/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777868/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-25","Africa: British Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the current status is of the British Council's African Knowledge Transfer Partnerships pilot project; and whether there are plans to continue or to replicate that project in the near future.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","109678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777869","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-30","<p>A Due Diligence assessment judges whether an organisation’s controls are adequate by assessing the extent to which they provide assurance that funds, assets, and people are managed effectively, and in line with DFID policies. This includes assessing whether they have internal policies in place to protect individuals from harm, and evidence that those policies are being robustly implemented.</p><p>We expect organisations which we fund directly to operate to the highest ethical standards and in line with their legal obligations. We hold them to account throughout the life of their agreement with DFID. Where partners employ local staff they must comply both with local legislation as well as the terms of the DFID agreement.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-10-30T17:55:50.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777869/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777869/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-25","Department for International Development: Sexual Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 19 October 2017 to Question 108856, on Developing countries: sexual harassment, how her Department defines adequate controls; and whether such controls were framed under the provisions of UK employment or in-country law.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","109762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777870","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-30","<p>DFID does not publish due diligence assessments.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-10-30T15:07:04.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777870/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777870/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-25","Department for International Development: Sexual Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 19 October 2017 to Question 108856, on Developing countries: sexual harassment, if the Government will publish the details of the due diligence assessment that organisations funded by her Department are subject to.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","109744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777871","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-30","<p>In the last eighteen months, 11 contracts above the OJEU threshold have been terminated for reasons including the programme’s underperformance, poor value for money, concerns regarding supplier capability, and changes in the delivery context. We have not established sexual harassment as a cause of any contract terminations. DFID’s new Supply Partner Code of Conduct requires suppliers to put whistleblowing arrangements in place, train their staff in ethical behaviour and human rights and ensure there is no exploitative treatment of workers in their supply chains.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-10-30T15:11:10.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777871/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777871/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-25","Department for International Development: Sexual Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 19 October 2017 to Question 108856, on Developing countries: sexual harassment, whether her Department has terminated any funding projects due to (a) suppliers not fulfilling their obligations and (b) reasons concerning sexual harassment policies or cases.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","109745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777872","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost. The Government is fully committed to making our prisons safe so that they can provide the maximum time out of cell for meaningful and purposeful activity to give prisoners the training, skills and work experience needed on release.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-03T14:44:28.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777872/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777872/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate the Government has made of the proportion of prisoners who spend more than 22 hours per day in their cell.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","109722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777873","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-30","<p>Early indicative estimates of the volumes of offenders starting with Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) annually were published as part of the ‘Transforming Rehabilitation: A Strategy for Reform’ consultation document, which can be found at: <a href="https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/transforming-rehabilitation/results/transforming-rehabilitation-response.pdf" target="_blank">https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/transforming-rehabilitation/results/transforming-rehabilitation-response.pdf</a>. It was always anticipated that volumes would vary through the life of the contract and we did not guarantee caseload levels to the providers.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2014, there have been changes in the case-mix of offenders and falls in the number of community orders. This has led to a proportionately lower number of cases being allocated to CRCs.</p><p> </p><p>To respond to these changes in volume, we changed the way we pay CRCs to reflect more accurately the costs of delivering services to offenders. This ensures they can focus on the delivery of those vital services.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-30T17:06:18.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777873/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777873/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders the Government projected would be referred to each community rehabilitation company in each quarter at the time of signing contracts with those companies.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","109753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777874","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-31","<p>As the UK’s departure from the European Union impacts upon most areas of departmental business, it is not possible to provide an estimate of the costs incurred by the department in this financial year.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-31T17:08:28.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777874/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777874/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Ministry of Justice: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the costs incurred by his Department in the current financial year in preparation for the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Stewart Hosie","Dundee East","Stewart Hosie","109623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777875","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-30","<p>We do not currently collate information centrally for the average number of hours prisoners spend on daily purposeful activity and it could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>We want prisons to be places of hard work and high ambition, with incentives for prisoners to learn.</p><p> </p><p>We have empowered Governors so they have more freedom to innovate and make the best decisions for their prisons. By next year, every governor will be able to tailor education and training to the needs of their prisoners, providing offenders the right support and challenge to help turn their backs on crime.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-30T17:19:05.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777875/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777875/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Prisoners: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average number of hours was that prisoners spent on purposeful activity in each day in (a) England and Wales and (b) each prison in England and Wales in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","109756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777876","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>Early indicative estimates of the volumes of offenders starting with Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) and the National Probation Service (NPS) annually were published as part of the ‘Transforming Rehabilitation: A Strategy for Reform’ consultation document, which can be found at: <a href="https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/transforming-rehabilitation/results/transforming-rehabilitation-response.pdf" target="_blank">https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/transforming-rehabilitation/results/transforming-rehabilitation-response.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Data on the number of offenders managed by the NPS and CRCs is published each quarter, and can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/offender-management-statistics-quarterly" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/offender-management-statistics-quarterly</a>. The estimates given in the Transforming Rehabilitation consultation document were based on offender starts, not total caseload.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-03T14:56:38.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777876/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777876/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of offenders are managed by the National Probation Services; and what proportion of offenders the Government estimated would be so managed at the time of that body's creation.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","109721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777877","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-31","<p>We published an Impact Assessment alongside our response to consultation –<a href="https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/lgfs-and-court-appointees/" target="_blank">https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/lgfs-and-court-appointees/</a></p><p> </p><p>There is no data to suggest that clients will not have access to the same criminal legal aid services as they do now. We are seeking to return expenditure to the levels they were before a Costs Judge decision in the case of Napper caused an unintended increase in expenditure. There is no evidence that those levels are no longer sustainable.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-31T17:10:36.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777877/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777877/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment the Government has made of the potential effect of its proposal to reduce the cap on the number of claimable pages under the Litigators' Graduated Fee Scheme on (a) historic sex abuse prosecutions and (b) other complex cases.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","109755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777878","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-30","<p>The number of cases allocated to Community Rehabilitation Companies in each quarter of the last two years is set out in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Q2 2015-16</p></td><td><p>Q3 2015-16</p></td><td><p>Q4 2015-16</p></td><td><p>Q1 2016-17</p></td><td><p>Q2 2016-17</p></td><td><p>Q3 2016-17</p></td><td><p>Q4 2016-17</p></td><td><p>Q1 2017-18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Allocated to CRC</p></td><td><p>42331</p></td><td><p>41615</p></td><td><p>42775</p></td><td><p>41665</p></td><td><p>39786</p></td><td><p>37565</p></td><td><p>41191</p></td><td><p>38540</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-30T17:00:20.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777878/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777878/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders have been referred to community rehabilitation companies in each quarter of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","109754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777879","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>From 1 April 2010 until 31 May 2014, provision was by 34 probation trusts in England and the Wales Probation Trust. The following table provides figures (full-time equivalents) for staff-in-post in probation trusts as at 30 June in each year from 2010 to 2013:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Staff-in-post</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>19,335</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>18,466</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>17,881</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>16,297</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>From 1 June 2014, probation services were provided by the National Probation Service (NPS) and 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs). At that point, both the NPS and the CRCs were in the public sector. Staff-in-post figures (full-time equivalents) for 30 June 2014 are shown in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>National Probation Service</p></td><td><p>Community Rehabilitation Companies</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>8,300</p></td><td><p>8,331</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>On 1 February 2015, the CRCs became private sector organisations, the NPS remaining within the public sector. Staff-in-post figures (full-time equivalents) as at 30 June 2014 for the NPS in the years 2015-17 are shown in the following table:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Staff-in-post</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>8,861</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>8,756</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>8,758</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>30 June 2017 is the latest date for which figures are available. Workforce figures as at 30 September are due to be published in November.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for the Community Rehabilitation Companies following their move to the private sector are not collected by the Ministry of Justice but contracts with CRCs require each CRC to ensure that it employs a sufficient level of staff, and that its workforce is competent and adequately trained. We closely monitor and robustly manage providers to make sure they fulfil their contractual commitments to reduce re-offending, protect the public and provide value for money to the taxpayer.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-03T14:47:20.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777879/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777879/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Probation: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff worked in the (a) public and (b) private probation sector (i) in each year since 2010 and (ii) on the latest date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","109713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777880","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service (HMPPS) is focused on giving IPP prisoners the support, opportunities and motivation they need to progress more quickly, so that once they have completed their tariff and are reviewed by the Parole Board, they have the best possible prospects for securing release.</p><p>Unto that end, and as part of a joint action plan with the Parole Board, HMPPS has implemented measures such as individual psychology-led central case reviews and increased access to specific offending behaviour programmes. Additionally, and building upon the success of the Progression Regime at HMP Warren Hill, HMPPS is planning for three new Progression Regimes to be opened by the end of March 2018.</p><p>These initiatives are working. During 2016/17, 46% of all IPP prisoners considered by the Parole Board were released and 24% recommended for a move to open conditions. 576 IPP prisoners were released in 2016, more than ever before. 315 IPP prisoners have already been released in the first half of 2017.</p><p>The attached table shows how many unreleased prisoners serving indeterminate sentences of Imprisonment for Public Protection (IPP) are located in each establishment and how many have served their minimum tariff.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","109512","2017-11-03T14:48:05.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777880/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777880/answer","109512 & 109714.xlsx","109512 & 109714.xlsx","Table 1","Table 1","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777880/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners serving imprisonment for public protection sentences there are in each prison; and how many such prisoners have already served their minimum tariff.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","109714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777881","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>6169 requests for a registered intermediary were received in 2016 and 5482 requests in 2017.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-03T14:50:16.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777881/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777881/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Registered Intermediaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many requests for registered intermediaries were made in (a) 2016 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","109707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777882","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>The number of requests for registered intermediaries received from the police and Crown Prosecution Service this year are detailed below. No requests were received from courts or solicitors.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Customer Type</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>0-4 years</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>5-11 years</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>12-17 years</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>18+ years</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>65+ years</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>CPS</strong></p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>482</p></td><td><p>267</p></td><td><p>415</p></td><td><p>32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Police</strong></p></td><td><p>497</p></td><td><p>1665</p></td><td><p>792</p></td><td><p>1198</p></td><td><p>113</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-03T14:50:45.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777882/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777882/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Registered Intermediaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many requests for registered intermediaries were made for each age group of vulnerable witnesses by (a) the police, (b) the Crown Prosecution Service, (c) courts and (d) solicitors in 2017.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","109710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777883","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally. Some Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) currently use telephone reporting as just one part of their operating models, in addition to regular reporting in person, where it is an appropriate tool for the individual case.</p><p> </p><p>Contract management teams continue to closely monitor and robustly manage providers to make sure they fulfil their contractual commitments to reduce reoffending, protect the public and provide value for money to the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>We have fundamentally reformed probation so that for the first time ever all offenders given a custodial sentence receive probation support. We remain in discussion with CRCs ensure our ambitious reforms are delivered successfully.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-03T14:45:22.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777883/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777883/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of probation assessments carried out by each community rehabilitation company were administered (a) by telephone and (b) face-to-face in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","109711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777884","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>The number of registered intermediaries available to cover each police force area in England and Wales are set out in the attached table.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-03T14:52:57.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777884/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777884/answer","109704.xlsx","109704.xlsx","Table 1","Table 1","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777884/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Registered Intermediaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many registered intermediaries are available to cover each police force in England and Wales in 2017.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","109704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777885","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>556 requests for a registered intermediary for a witness under 18 years old have been received from the Crown Prosecution Service. Of these, 526 were matched, 17 unmatched, 8 cancelled and 5 are in progress.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-03T14:52:33.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777885/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777885/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Registered Intermediaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many sexual offences were prosecuted which involved a person aged under 18-years old where that person was (a) matched and (b) unmatched with a registered intermediary in 2017.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","109702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777886","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>Details of requests for registered intermediary support from the police and Crown Prosecution Service are set out in the attached table. No requests have been received from defence lawyers or judges.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-03T14:48:34.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777886/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777886/answer","109703.xlsx","109703.xlsx","Table 1","Table 1","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777886/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Registered Intermediaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many requests for registered intermediary support there were for witnesses (a) under and (b) over 18-years old by (i) the police, (ii) the Crown Prosecution Service, (iii) defence lawyers, (iv) judges and (v) police area in 2017; and what proportion of those requests were successfully fulfilled for each of such category of witness and requester.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","109703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777887","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-30","<p>The Safety in Custody statistics, published quarterly at <em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/safety-in-custody-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/safety-in-custody-statistics</a>, </em>show that the number of self-inflicted deaths in prisons has fallen by 30%, from 110 in the year to September 2016 to 77 in the year to September 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Every self-inflicted death in custody is a tragedy, and the Government takes very seriously its responsibility to keep prisoners safe. We have established a prison safety programme that includes a comprehensive set of actions to prevent self-inflicted deaths, including: rolling out revised and improved training for staff; improving support for prisoners in their early days in custody; revising the ACCT case management process for those identified as being at risk; and funding the Samaritans to provide their valuable Listeners Scheme.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","109680","2017-10-30T17:05:11.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777887/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777887/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Prisoners: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to reduce the number of self-inflicted deaths of prisoners.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","109679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777888","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-30","<p>The Safety in Custody statistics, published quarterly at <em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/safety-in-custody-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/safety-in-custody-statistics</a>, </em>show that the number of self-inflicted deaths in prisons has fallen by 30%, from 110 in the year to September 2016 to 77 in the year to September 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Every self-inflicted death in custody is a tragedy, and the Government takes very seriously its responsibility to keep prisoners safe. We have established a prison safety programme that includes a comprehensive set of actions to prevent self-inflicted deaths, including: rolling out revised and improved training for staff; improving support for prisoners in their early days in custody; revising the ACCT case management process for those identified as being at risk; and funding the Samaritans to provide their valuable Listeners Scheme.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","109679","2017-10-30T17:05:11.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777888/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777888/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Prisoners: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of recent trends in the number of self-inflicted deaths in prisons.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","109680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777889","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunal Service (HMCTS) is very sensitive to the needs of people with a wide range of physical and mental challenges. Tribunal staff, and judicial office holders, are trained accordingly, with the HMCTS reasonable adjustments policy, and guidance on this policy is published.</p><p>Anyone starting an appeal before the Tribunal is asked at the outset on the appeal form if they have any special needs requirements and made aware that they can have a friend or other helper with them if they wish to attend the hearing. If they do not want to attend, the appeal can be decided as a paper hearing. In rare circumstances, the hearing might be held at the appellant's home, or a medical centre</p><p><br>The Tribunal is an informal and non-adversarial forum for the settling of disputes, and the judge and panel members are highly experienced and expert in their fields. A personal independence payment hearing will have a panel made up of a judge, a doctor and a person with experience or relevant qualification in disability matters. During the hearing the panel will be attentive to the circumstances and needs of the appellant, and a hearing can be paused for a rest break where required.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-03T14:52:12.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777889/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777889/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effect on people with autism of participating in a potentially stressful personal independence payment tribunal.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","109609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777890","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-30","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-10-30T17:52:41.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777890/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777890/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Ministry of Justice: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much his Department spent on staff attending external courses in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","109681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777891","Home Office","false","2017-11-27","<p>The Home Office Statistical Bulletin publishes data about convictions quarterly but does not distinguish those which relate to Syria and Daesh. British Citizens who are investigated and charged with offences relating to the conflict in Syria will be prosecuted in accordance with the Code for Crown Prosecutors.</p><p>Although official figures do not show how many were Syria or Daesh related, Of the 105 persons charged with a terrorism-related offence in the year ending June 2017, 33 had been prosecuted (as at the time of data provision to the Home Office, 14 July 2017), 32 of which were found guilty. A further 68 were awaiting prosecution.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-11-27T17:54:26.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777891/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777891/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-25","British Nationals Abroad: Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many British citizens who have returned to the UK after fighting in Iraq and Syria since 2012 have been prosecuted.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","109590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777892","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-30","<p>Data on the gender and residence of members of the magistracy is collected by my Department. The cross referencing and collation of the data required to answer Question 107170 could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-30T17:25:14.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777892/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777892/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Magistrates: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 18 October 2017 to Question 107170 on magistrates: Warrington, when and for what reasons his Department decided to cease collection of data on the gender and residence of members of the magistracy.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","109566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777893","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-30","<p>The Government is committed to removing Foreign National Offenders (FNOs) from the United Kingdom, with a record number of over 6,300 removed from prisons, immigration removal centres (IRCs) and the community in 2016/17.</p><p> </p><p>As at 30 September 2017, 4,125 nationals from other EU countries were held in prisons (including HMPPS, run immigration removal centres) in England and Wales. 2,943 of these were serving sentence of imprisonment. A total of 217 EU nationals have been transferred to prisons in their own country under the EU Prisoner Transfer Framework Decision since it entered into force in December 2011. In 2016/17 we removed 110 prisoners under all transfer arrangements to countries around the world, and this financial year have transferred a further 56 prisoners worldwide. We are continuing to work with governments across the world to drive up these transfer figures further.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-30T17:02:59.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777893/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777893/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Prisoners: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many EU nationals (a) are in UK prisons and (b) have been transferred to prison in their own countries under the EU Prisoner Transfer Directive.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","109565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777894","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>We are committed to doing all we can to address the issues around female offending so we can better protect the public and deliver more effective rehabilitation. We know that female offenders have complex and specific rehabilitative needs and as part of our estates transformation programme we are, for the first time, designing community prisons tailored to the needs of women.</p><p>We will continue to explore options for potential new sites for women’s prisons and will outline further proposals in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","109577","2017-11-03T14:38:40.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777894/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777894/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Women's Prisons: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he plans to build a new women's prison in Wales; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","109576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777895","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>We are committed to doing all we can to address the issues around female offending so we can better protect the public and deliver more effective rehabilitation. We know that female offenders have complex and specific rehabilitative needs and as part of our estates transformation programme we are, for the first time, designing community prisons tailored to the needs of women.</p><p>We will continue to explore options for potential new sites for women’s prisons and will outline further proposals in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","109576","2017-11-03T14:38:40.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777895/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777895/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Prisons: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he plans to build a new women's prison in England; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","109577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777896","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-03","<p>The Government is carrying out an ongoing programme of comprehensive analytical work that will inform our negotiating position with the EU, to define our deep and special partnership with the EU and inform our understanding of how EU exit will affect the UK’s domestic policies and frameworks.</p><p>The Ministry of Justice is working with officials across government, in close coordination with the Department for Exiting the European Union, to ensure the delivery of a holistic programme of analysis across government.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-03T14:50:52.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777896/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777896/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-25","Ministry of Justice: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department was consulted by the Department for Exiting the European Union on the economic impact assessments conducted for the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","109538"
