"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777933","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-30","<p>Representations from Honourable Members are handled by specialist correspondence teams within the Department. These teams liaise with the relevant area of the Department to provide an appropriate response. The Department has an established feedback process which would be used should Case Managers and Decision Makers need to be made aware of representations by Honourable Members.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-30T11:57:56.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777933/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777933/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-25","Department for Work and Pensions: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how representations from hon. members acting on behalf of constituents about benefit claim decisions are communicated to case managers and decision makers working for his Department.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","109642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777934","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-01","<p>All Jobcentres across Wales and Great Britain have had customer computers and free to use wi-fi since 2014/15, replacing the customer access telephones and jobpoints in place prior to this. This reflects increased digital capability and accessibility, improving services for all customers regardless of their location.</p><p> </p><p>There are more than 8,000 computers available to support customers who need help with making their claim digitally and applying for jobs on line across the Jobcentre network. However, customers who require access to a phone in connection with their benefit or job search will still be given access to a telephone in a Jobcentre.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-01T14:27:25.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777934/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777934/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-25","Jobcentres: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which jobcentres in Wales have offered claimants free access to jobcentre (a) telephone lines and (b) computers in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","109612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777935","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-01","<p>Information on the number of times jobcentre computers were accessed by claimants in each jobcentre in Wales is not collected. The table PQ109613 attached in Annex 1 shows the number of Wireless Access Devices (WADs) allocated to each Jobcentre in Wales, and the number of times the WI-FI facility at each Jobcentre in Wales was accessed, in August 2017 (latest data available).</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-11-01T14:34:57.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777935/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777935/answer","PQ109613 Annex 1.docx","PQ109613 Annex 1.docx","PQ109613 Annex 1","PQ109613 Annex 1","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777935/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-25","Jobcentres: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many times jobcentre computers were accessed by claimants in each jobcentre in Wales in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","109613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777936","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-01","<p>The information is not available and can only be provided at disproportionate costs</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-11-01T14:36:52.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777936/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777936/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-25","Jobcentres: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many telephone calls were made by benefit claimants from within each jobcentre in Wales in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","109614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777937","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-30","<p>We currently have approximately 440 people nationally at risk of redundancy, less than our original estimate, as a result of the changes to our estate. These people work in a wide variety of job roles and functions, which includes those working or based in jobcentres, processing centres and in Corporate Centre roles.</p><p> </p><p>However we expect this number to reduce as we redeploy as many people as we can across DWP and other government departments. We are continuing redeployment activity and therefore the number at risk may still reduce further. To place these fissures in context the overall DWP workforce is approximately 80,000.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-30T16:03:38.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777937/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777937/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777937/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-25","Jobcentres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of jobs that will be affected by the closure of jobcentres; and what the roles and functions of those jobs will be.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","109688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777938","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-02","<p>I responded to your letter on 30 October. As explained in the reply there have been good reasons for the delay.</p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-11-02T12:16:21.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777938/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777938/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777938/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-25","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for Weston-Super-Mare, of 11 August 2017, on behalf of Somerset Savings & Loans on the Credit Union Expansion Project.","false","Biography information for John Penrose","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","109604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777939","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-02","<p>The latest available information on national Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) clearance times can be found in Table 18 of the ESA Outcomes of Work Capability Assessments quarterly statistics published here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/employment-and-support-allowance-outcomes-of-work-capability-assessment" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/employment-and-support-allowance-outcomes-of-work-capability-assessment</a></p><p> </p><p>This information is not readily available at constituency level and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","109773","2017-11-02T16:35:00.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777939/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777939/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777939/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-25","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average waiting time was between an employment and support allowance claim application and a first payment being made (a) nationally and (b) in Sunderland Central constituency in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","109735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777940","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-02","<p>Support is available to claimants to help them make the transition to Universal Credit. Universal Support is help for those who need assistance to manage their claim online and/or help with budgeting in order to manage their monthly payments and prioritise essential bills such as rent and utilities. Where claimants have no capability to make or manage their claim on-line, telephone and face to face support is available. Alternatively, an Appointee could make the claim on their behalf and maintain their online account.</p><p> </p><p>We are continuously reviewing and improving the service for vulnerable people who claim UC, including how they are identified and supported both internally and via referral to local services delivered in partnership activity with other relevant agencies and organisations.</p><p> </p><p>Identifying skills needs (sometimes called skills screenings) is an integral part of work coach meetings with claimants. This process involves observation and discussion to gather evidence on skills, qualifications, previous training and work history.</p><p> </p><p>The information gathered determines whether the claimant has any potential skills gaps in relation to their individual job goals and jobs readily available in the local labour market.</p><p> </p><p>Where further investigation is needed for potential basic skills needs (English/maths/ICT) claimants can be asked to complete the paper-based Fast Track Screening Tool. The tool is a short series of questions completed by the claimant and marked by the work coach to indicate potential basic skills needs.</p><p> </p><p>Where a potential skills need is identified, the claimant can then be referred to an initial assessment with a learning provider (DfE funded through the Adult Education Budget) to confirm their skill level or alternatively referred for a more detailed assessment with the National Careers Service or equivalent in Scotland and Wales.</p><p> </p><p>Work Coaches use the evidence gathered through the initial screening and subsequent provider assessment to decide what remedial training or other action is required to help the claimant find work.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-02T16:08:31.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777940/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777940/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777940/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-25","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to assist universal credit claimants who are (a) illiterate or (b) innumerate.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","109620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777941","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-02","<p>a) The information is not readily available and can only be provided at disproportionate costs</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>b) The average speed of answer for each of the claim lines in the Department’s agencies for the last year (April 16 to March 17) is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Claim lines in the Department’s agencies</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Average Speed of Answer (ASA)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Employment Support Allowance</p></td><td><p>00:06:14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jobseekers Allowance</p></td><td><p>00:02:42</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Income Support</p></td><td><p>00:04:34</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Personal Independence Payment</p></td><td><p>00:04:06</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Special Rules for Terminally Ill</p></td><td><p>00:01:36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Universal Credit Full Service</p></td><td><p>00:07:26</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Universal Credit Live Service</p></td><td><p>00:03:08</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>State Pension and Pension Credit (combined)</p></td><td><p>00:01:46</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Carers Allowance</p></td><td><p>00:02:34</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Attendance Allowance (including Disability Living Allowance for aged 65+)</p></td><td><p>00:01:11</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-11-02T12:32:08.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777941/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777941/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/777941/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-25","Department for Work and Pensions: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average time was for answering telephone calls for each category of claim handled by (a) jobcentres in Wales and (b) his Department's agencies in each year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","109621"
